item.description:
Simple cache manger came out of a need to get rid of some bulky libraries to do the simple caching of data. It&rsquo;s only a couple of classes and easy to just copy-paste into your project.
Here is the API:
{% highlight c# %} var cacheManager = new CacheManager(); cacheManager.Add(&ldquo;key1&rdquo;, &ldquo;value1&rdquo;, DateTime.UtcNow, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(300)); cacheManager.Add(&ldquo;key2&rdquo;, &ldquo;value2&rdquo;, DateTime.UtcNow, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(600));
Assert.True(cacheManager.Contains(&ldquo;key1&rdquo;)); Assert.True(cacheManager.Contains(&ldquo;key1&rdquo;));
Assert.Equal(&ldquo;value1&rdquo;, cacheManager.GetData(&ldquo;key1&rdquo;)); Assert.Equal(&ldquo;value1&rdquo;, cacheManager.GetData(&ldquo;key1&rdquo;)); {% endhighlight %}
It&rsquo;s as simple as that.

This is a quick and dirty example of how you can enable a simple form of logging for clients using ASP.NET Web API. I used log4net and an extremely simple controller to achieve this.
Controller has only a couple of tricks to get the body of the POST as it is regardless of the content type. The rest is pretty straight forward.
{% highlight c# %} public class LogController : ApiController {
